title: For Sale:  Japanese Type 38 Arisaka
postcontent: Considering selling this piece to make room and fund a different gun for my collection.  This is a Japanese Type 38 Arisaka long rifle, chambered in 6.5x55.  From my research, it was made at the Koishikawa arsenal in Tokyo prior to 1935.Mum is ground, as is common.  Bolt does not match the reciever (again, as common), with a mismatched extractor and I can't make out the firing pin markings.  I've never had any indication of punctured primers or deep strikes that I've noticed, so the firing pin matches close enough not to be an issue.  Components of the rifle are mismatched a bit, as well.  The bolt release and end cap are different numbered than the receiver SN.The bore is in good condition, sharp rifling and only some dust and such from sitting in the cabinet.  No rust or pitting that I can tell.  It does have a cleaning rod, though I don't know enough about them to tell if it's original or reproduction.This is a good shooter that's also a good piece if you're into WWII or Pacific theatre items.  I've shot several rounds through it.  It's not a hard kicker at all and is accurate.  Would make a nice ont to take out to the range on occassion and it's long enough to get some attention and discussion.I have more pics if needed and can get you more information on request.  I'm willing to ship to C&R or FFL holders for actual cost of shipping.
